english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister Choi of Gaizhou
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Among the Presented Scholars known throughout the Eastern Lands under the Imperial Court was one called Choi Suong of Gyerim. He was first appointed Judge of Gaizhou, a remote place with burdensome duties. After five months, worn by illness, he returned eastward to his homeland and took no further service with the Yuan. Though he served his own country, his talents were singular and his ambitions lofty—too lofty for the times to bear. At fifty-four years of age, in the sixth year of Zhiyuan, in the sixth month on the tenth day, he departed this world from illness. His younger brother, the Censor Jae, brought to me the account of his life and begged for this epitaph, saying: "My brother's talents were not inferior to the ancients, yet his vision never took root in this world. In the end his office remained modest, his years few. He left no legacy to benefit others, no sons to continue his line. If I do not have his deeds inscribed in the darkness of the tomb and numbered among the records, then I betray my brother. None know him as well as you do. I beg you write his epitaph." How could I refuse such a plea? So I have set down his lineage and recorded the truth of his life.

    The Minister's personal name was Hae, also known as Yanmyeongbu. His distant ancestor Yunshun served in Silla, rising to the rank of Grand Commandant, and the family dwelt for generations in Gyerim. His great-grandfather served as Military Inspector of Gyeongju and was posthumously honored as Judge of the Military Records. His grandfather held the rank of Inspector of Military Armaments and was posthumously honored as Judge of the Land Registry. His father, Baeklun, achieved the highest honors in the civil examinations and was renowned at court. He was appointed Royal Confucian Instructor of Goryeo and through successive promotions became Minister of the People's Department, with the rank of Eminent Grand Counselor. His mother, of the Rhim clan, was enfeoffed as Lady of Jinyang and was the daughter of the Grand General at Retirement.

    From his youth the Minister showed extraordinary brilliance. At nine years old he composed poetry with facility. As he matured, his learning advanced daily and earned him great praise from elder scholars. Before reaching twenty, he twice took the examinations in rhetoric and belles-lettres, and passed both times. He was first dismissed from his post as Instructor at the National Academy, then selected as Examiner at the Offices of Literary Studies and the Annals. Shortly after, through some matter, he was demoted to Overseer of the Long Sands Warehouse. Later he was again selected as Assistant Registrar at the Offices of Literary Studies and the Annals. From that post he was promoted to Director of the Changhung Treasury, then advanced through successive positions to become Vice-Director of the National Academy, Assistant Professor of Literary Studies, Custodian of Ceremonies, and finally Inspector General of the National Academy.

    In his studies the Minister read widely and composed with refinement, yet relied not on teachers or friends for instruction. He transcended these, arriving at understanding through his own illumination of principle. He was not deceived by heterodox teachings, nor seduced by vulgar customs, but sought always to accord with the ancients. When questions of agreement and disagreement arose, if he perceived the truth, he would even challenge and refute those whom the age honored as masters, holding his own views with unwavering certainty. Such was the nature of his learning.

    When the examinations were announced during the Yanyou period, he said to himself: "Now I shall test what I have learned." And indeed, he achieved the highest place in the examinations of the year Xinyu. The Censor Song praised his talents often in verse, and from this his fame spread. Yet those who differed from him grew only more hostile, seeking to suppress him. The Minister was not skilled in court intrigue, was bold and outspoken, and delighted in speaking of others' virtues and faults—thus he would be suddenly elevated, then suddenly cast down. In the end, he was never greatly employed.

    Yet he chose his friends with discernment, understood his fate, and was not troubled. He did not let office bring him joy or its loss bring him sorrow, but found contentment in poetry and wine. In his lifetime he selected the works of eminent worthies of his country, compiled them into a collection called "Writings of Eastern Men"—twenty-five volumes in all. He never concerned himself with household management or the accumulation of wealth, calling himself "the Unpolished One." In his later years he dwelt at the foot of Lion Mountain south of the capital, opened a garden which he named "Sufficiency," and became known as "the Recluse Farmer of Lion Mountain." When he died and was buried on the eastern slope of that mountain, his family was in poverty, yet all who had known him competed in sending gifts of sympathy, thus enabling a proper funeral.

    The Minister married twice. His first wife was the daughter of Censor Pan Yongyuan; she bore him one daughter who married the gentleman Jee Seop. His second wife was the daughter of Cae Heung of the Gate of Proper Ritual; she bore him two daughters, both young at the time of his death. He left no sons.

    The Epitaph reads:

    Ah, Minister Choi of old!
    Alone you stood, unbowed by the crowd,
    Your learning drawn from ancient depths,
    Your writings treasured what the past had shown.
    Resolute against the world's decay,
    Bold-tongued, you spoke what others dared not say—
    Your years were few, yet fame endures,
    No sons to bear your name,
    Yet brothers guard your memory's shrine.
    You held to virtue, I to rank—
    Who lost, and who has gained?
    You questioned nothing, grieved not then,
    Why should I grieve for you?

    On Lion Mountain's eastern slope,
    A horse-mane mound awaits the ages,
    Though thousand years have passed and will,
    The Unpolished One is known still.
