  - key: ''
    value: Gyerim (鷄林) is the classical name for Gyeongju, the ancient Silla capital; it metonymically refers to Korea itself.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to "Zhiyuan 6" (至元六年) appears to contain a dating discrepancy in the original text, as Zhiyuan 6 would be 1269, well before Choi's time. The Korean commentary notes this refers to the first year of King Chungsuk's restoration.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase "Scion of the sage" (私淑) refers to the Confucian practice of learning from ancient masters through their writings rather than direct instruction.
  - key: ''
    value: The "Unpolished One" (拙翁) was Choi's chosen sobriquet, expressing both humility and a refusal to polish himself for worldly advancement.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Gok (李穀, 1298-1351) was a prominent scholar-official of Goryeo and one of the era's major literary figures, known for his mastery of both Korean and Chinese letters.
